<LP>
   A BROAD ECONOMIC PACT was reached by the U.S. and Japan
that is intended to make it easier for foreigners to do
business in Japan. The accord also calls for the U.S. to
increase savings and competitiveness. Still, the landmark
agreement will require legislative changes in both nations,
which may be hard to achieve.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A House panel approved clean-air legislation after
adopting an acid rain package that would help Midwest
utilities facing cleanup costs. The bill may reach the House
floor in May.
   ---
   UAL directors began merger talks with United Air's unions
following a sweetened union offer of $200 a share, or $4.36
billion. The decision to negotiate signaled that the board
may be ready to accept the bid rather than wage a proxy
battle with UAL's largest shareholder, Coniston Partners.
   ---
   Ford is holding talks about the possible sale of its New
Holland farm-equipment unit to Fiat of Italy, sources said. A
sale would mark Ford's second major retreat from
diversification in recent months.
   ---
   The thrift-bailout program is now widely expected to cost
at least twice as much as the $157.6 billion that Bush
officials were estimating last year. The new projection
leaves a funding gap of $100 billion to $200 billion.
   ---
   Browning-Ferris plans to sell its hazardous waste-disposal
business following problems complying with environmental
rules. The move may result in a $295 million charge.
   ---
   Bankruptcy-law filings jumped 34% in the fourth quarter of
last year, reflecting the soft economy and heavy debt burdens
at many companies. The growth appears likely to continue.
   ---
   Stock exchanges are seeking the authority to charge fees
for price quotations they regularly provide for free. The
proposal has sparked a major dispute between the Big Board
and brokerage and media firms.
   ---
   Japan's securities industry is expected to undergo a major
shake-up following the collapse in Tokyo share prices this
year. The changes may mean stiffer competition for U.S. and
European brokerages in Japan.
   ---
   Vernon S&amp;L ex-chairman Woody Lemons was sentenced to 30
years in prison for fraud and other charges relating to the
1987 collapse of the Dallas thrift. It is one of the stiffest
sentences ever in an S&amp;L fraud case.
   ---
   Petroleum prices tumbled on worries about a possible
supply glut. OPEC production is now at an eightyear high,
while U.S. crude inventories are the biggest in two years.
   ---
   Eight publicly traded funds originally sponsored by VMS
Realty Partners are delaying dividend declarations. Three are
suspending payouts.
   ---
   Newspaper advertising has been weaker than expected this
year, surprising publishers. Ad revenue is flat or down at
papers across the country, especially in the Northeast.
   ---
   Major retailers posted weak sales for March, reflecting
the later Easter holiday season and continued sluggish demand
for some durable goods. Also, many retail chains don't report
March sales until next week.
